Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** for the (hypothetical) C++ library **`libpcapng`**.  
It consists of

* an OCaml interface file `pcapng.mli`,
* a C‑C++ stub file `pcapng_stubs.cpp`,
* a tiny helper header `pcapng_wrapper.hpp` that hides the C++ details from the stub.

You can drop the three files into a directory, add a small `dune` stanza (or a classic `Makefile` – see the end) and you will have an OCaml module `Pcapng` that

```ocaml
let r = Pcapng.open_file "capture.pcapng" in
Pcapng.iter_frames r (fun f ->
  Printf.printf "frame %Ld len=%d\n%!"
    (Int64.of_int f.ts_sec) f.caplen);
Pcapng.close r
```

The binding does the **right thing** with the OCaml garbage collector, runs the user‑supplied callback **outside the runtime lock** (so long‑running C++ code does not block other OCaml threads), and cleans up the C++ objects automatically with a finaliser.

---

## 1.  OCaml public interface – `pcapng.mli`

```ocaml
(** pcapng.mli – public OCaml API for libpcapng *)

(** A handle to an opened pcapng file.  The concrete type is abstract
    and is managed by the OCaml runtime (it is freed automatically when
    it becomes unreachable, but you may also call [close] explicitly). *)
type t

(** Information about a single captured frame.  All fields are copied
    from the underlying C++ object, so the OCaml value owns its own
    memory. *)
type frame = {
  ts_sec   : int;      (** Timestamp seconds since the epoch *)
  ts_usec  : int;      (** Timestamp micro‑seconds part *)
  caplen   : int;      (** Number of bytes actually captured *)
  origlen  : int;      (** Original length of the packet on the wire *)
  data     : bytes;    (** Payload – exactly [caplen] bytes *)
}

(** Open a pcapng file.  Raises [Failure msg] if the file cannot be read
    or the format is unsupported. *)
val open_file : string -> t

(** Iterate over all frames in the file.  For each frame the supplied
    OCaml callback is invoked exactly once.  The iteration runs in the
    C++ library, the OCaml callback is called with the runtime lock
    reacquired, so it may perform any OCaml operation (including
    allocating new values).  If the callback raises, the iteration is
    aborted and the exception propagates to the caller. *)
val iter_frames : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit

(** Explicitly close the handle.  After a call to [close] the handle
    must not be used again.  The function is idempotent (calling it
    twice is a no‑op). *)
val close : t -> unit
```

