## 5.  Using the binding from OCaml

```ocaml
(* demo.ml – a tiny example program *)
let () =
  let file = Sys.argv.(1) in
  let rdr = Pcapng.open_file file in
  Printf.printf "Opened %s\n%!" file;
  Pcapng.iter_frames rdr (fun f ->
    Printf.printf "frame ts=%d.%06d caplen=%d origlen=%d\n%!"
      f.ts_sec f.ts_usec f.caplen f.origlen);
  Pcapng.close rdr
```

Compile the demo (with dune or the Makefile) and run:

```sh
$ ./demo.exe capture.pcapng
Opened capture.pcapng
frame ts=1629387205.123456 caplen=64 origlen=64
frame ts=1629387205.123789 caplen=128 origlen=128
...
```

The **callback runs in the OCaml world**, so you can freely allocate values,
raise exceptions, use `Lwt`, etc.  Because the heavy lifting (reading the file,
walking the iterator) happens while the OCaml runtime lock is released, the
binding works nicely in multithreaded programs.

---

### TL;DR – What you get

| Symbol | OCaml type | Meaning |
|--------|------------|---------|
| `type t` | abstract | handle to an opened pcapng file |
| `type frame` | record | `{ ts_sec; ts_usec; caplen; origlen; data }` |
| `open_file : string -> t` | → | open a file |
| `iter_frames : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit` | → | walk all frames, invoking the supplied callback |
| `close : t -> unit` | → | free resources (optional, finaliser does it as well) |

Feel free to adapt the `frame` record (add more fields, change the timestamp
type, etc.) and the C++ wrapper to match the exact API of the real
`libpcapng` you are binding to. The pattern – **custom block + finaliser +
runtime‑lock juggling** – works for any C++ iterator that you want to expose
as an OCaml callback loop. Happy hacking!
